The equation for simple harmonic motion is given by:
\begin{equation}
    x = A \sin(\omega t)
\end{equation}

where \( \omega = \frac{2\pi}{T} \).

Given that the amplitude drops by a factor of \( \frac{1}{e} \) in 8 periods, we can relate this to the quality factor \( Q \) using the formula:
\begin{equation}
    Q = \frac{\pi N}{\ln(\text{amplitude reduction factor})}
\end{equation}

Substituting \( N = 8 \) and the amplitude reduction factor as \( e \), we have:
\begin{equation}
    Q = \frac{\pi \times 8}{\ln(e)} = 8\pi
\end{equation}

\section{Calculation of Mass in SHM}

Given:
\begin{align*}
    \omega &= 2\pi \\
    T &= \frac{2\pi}{\omega} = 1 \, \text{rad/s} \\
    8\sqrt{2} &= A \sin\left(\frac{\pi}{4}\right) \\
    A &= 16 \, \text{cm} = 0.16 \, \text{m}
\end{align*}

The energy \( E \) in SHM is given by:
\begin{equation}
    E = \frac{1}{2} m A^2 \omega^2
\end{equation}

